nteraction between Sonoran indigenous groups and Spanish settlers grew in complexity and intensity, due in part to the implementation of reform-minded Bourbon policies which envisioned a more secular, productive, and modern society. At the same time, new forms of what this book identifies as pluriethnic mobility also emerged. Franciscan missionaries and mission residents deployed diverse strategies to cope with these changes and results varied from region to region, depending on such factors as the missionaries' backgrounds, Indian responses to mission life, local economic arrangements, and cultural exchanges between Indians and Spaniards.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aFranciscanszMexicozSonora (State)xHistoryy18th century. 0aFranciscanszMexicozSonora (State)xHistoryy19th century. 0aIndians of MexicoxMissionszMexicozSonora (State)xHistoryy18th century. 0aIndians of MexicoxMissionszMexicozSonora (State)xHistoryy19th century. 0aMissionszMexicozSonora (State)xHistoryy18th century. 0aMissionszMexicozSonora (State)xHistoryy19th century. 0aSocial structurezMexicozSonora (State)xHistoryy18th century. 0aSocial structurezMexicozSonora (State)xHistoryy19th century. 4aArizona. 4aFranciscans. 4aOpata Indians. 4aPapago Indians. 4aPima Indians. 4aSonora. 4acultural change. 4ahorizontal mobility. 4amissions. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478732140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804787321423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804787321.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles